  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">James Miller M&apos;Kim explains that Mr. (Edwin Lawrence) Godkin&apos;s stay in Boston was too short to enable him to call on Maria Weston Chapman. M&apos;Kim says: &quot;The Nation will start under the most favorable auspices. Now that its establishment is an accomplished fact my connection with it ceases.&quot; [Ewin Lawrence Godkin founded The Nation in 1865.] J. Miller M&apos;Kim is secretary of the American Freedmen&apos;s Aid Union. The function of the Freedmen&apos;s Aid movement is &quot;the enlightenment of the newly liberated blacks (by schools &amp; the like), &amp; of the unliberated &amp; half liberated whites -- north &amp; south -- as to their duties to the blacks.&quot; J. Miller M&apos;Kim want the aid of Maria W. Chapman and her sisters and daughters &quot;in making this movement what it ought to be.&quot;</subfield>
